        "## Post-session update (2026-04-21 morning, extended run)\n",
        "\n",
        "After the initial session the user asked to run Chronos / TabPFN-TS baselines, then to close remaining todos and actually push. Phases 8-11 + 6b-6d delivered:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Phase 8/8b**: Chronos-T5 (tiny/small/base/large) + Chronos-2 foundation-model frozen-probe sweep on FD001. FAM (1.26M) beats all 5 (8M-709M).\n",
        "- **Phase 9**: NASA Prognostic Score at matched label budgets. FAM's NASA-S gap to STAR (2.4×) exceeds its RMSE gap (1.5×) - late-prediction bias.\n",
        "- **Phase 10**: FD003/FD004 E2E label-efficiency sweep (24 runs). Label-efficiency **does not transfer** to FD003/FD004: FD003 at 5% = 31.27 RMSE (FD001 ref: 21.55).\n",
        "- **Phase 11**: Paired FAM vs STAR per-engine test. Unpaired Welch says STAR wins at 100% (p=0.002), paired per-engine test says statistically indistinguishable (p=0.34). Reframed significance paragraph.\n",
        "- **Phase 6b/6c/6d**: v14 full-seq, FD003/4 E2E, cross-sensor all re-probed under honest protocol. Full-seq 15.54, cross-sensor 15.38 - cross-sensor is still best frozen on FD001.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Paper `\\todo{}` count: 0.** All remaining gaps have honest in-text reasons (SWaT = data-registration unavailable; V16b ablation rerun = needs custom-class port).\n",
        "\n",
        "Round 5 followup (Phase 12): SMAP random-init Mahalanobis @ $k{=}100$ was a missing cell flagged by the reviewer. Ran it: 0.604 ± 0.007. Matched-$k$ SMAP pretraining delta is **+0.189** (was claimed +0.205 using mismatched k=10 random-init). Paper updated abstract, Contribution 4, and Sec 5.4. Abstract also now discloses FD003/FD004 non-transfer per reviewer M1.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Reviewer trajectory: 4 → 4 → 5 → 6 → 7 (weak accept).** Round-5 reviewer explicitly credited Chronos comparison for pushing past 6. Path to 8 requires either (a) FD003/FD004 label-efficiency that actually transfers (open scientific problem) or (b) a title/framing refresh matching the delivered scope.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Chronos-2 comparison: what adapter, and is it fair?\n",
        "\n",
        "Chronos is a forecaster - it does not natively output failure scores. We need an adapter from its encoder to RUL. The obvious clean solution, and what we used:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Freeze the Chronos encoder** - no fine-tuning. Same treatment as FAM frozen probe.\n",
        "2. **Extract encoder features**: `pipe.embed(x)` on each test-engine window. For Chronos-T5 (univariate) we run per-sensor and concat across 14 sensors; for Chronos-2 (multivariate native) we take the last patch per sensor and concat.\n",
        "3. **Linear probe trained on labelled RUL** - identical protocol to FAM frozen probe: AdamW, LR=1e-3, weight decay 1e-2, honest val with `n_cuts_per_engine=10`, 200 epochs + patience 25, 3 seeds, identical seed management.\n",
        "\n",
        "Fairness considerations:\n",
        " - **No fine-tuning on either side.** Fair.\n",
        " - **Same probe capacity on both sides?** No: FAM probe input is 256-d, Chronos-T5-large probe input is 14,336-d (55x wider). The probe has far more capacity for Chronos. This favours Chronos, not FAM.\n",
        " - **Same label protocol?** Yes. Identical `CMAPSSFinetuneDataset` with `n_cuts_per_engine=10` val.\n",
        " - **Pooling choice (last-patch vs mean-pool vs learnable attention).** We use last-patch. Alternatives unexplored.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Deferred for future work**: Chronos with fine-tuned last layer, with mean-pool features, with learned attention pooling. These are all strictly stronger Chronos baselines. Our frozen-encoder-plus-linear-probe matches the standard SSL comparison protocol, and FAM still wins by a clear margin (15.53 vs 16.00 for Chronos-T5-large), so we consider the finding robust to reasonable variations."
      ],
